So something interesting I am trying really hard to figure out

for some reason this isn't well talked about but there are two very different types of "at rest" encryption. Encryption of a column (like encrypting a message). And encryption of a volume (encrypting the entire hard drive).

Encryption of a volume is extremely easy and AWS, Fly, and all providers do this. Encryption of a column is much, much, much, more difficult, since we'd have to decrypt messages before searching them or do some funky ass shit to search.

I have been searching and searching and I can't find which one Slack is doing... makes me think they are doing the easier path, but idk...

@Walshhh It seems slack does encrypt messages per column

Imo this is really good for us as this means they simply don't have the ability to give direct SQL access to Large Language Models

I found an article *written by Slack* that says they store their messages in MySQL https://slack.engineering/scaling-datastores-at-slack-with-vitess/. They just have some intense sharding to get it to scale properly.

This was my bad, because when I researched last month I read an article from a third party that said they store messages in DynamoDB, but that seems to be innaccurate.

However, since they encrypt the "plaintext" of the data in the database and rely on search indexes to search through the "encrypted data" then we a good moat since raw SQL access would be useless if they encrypt this stuff. And you can't run MySQL on memory so you can't do that funky stuff we are doing. And they encrypt IDs... which like... wtf are you going to do at that point loll

Additionally, MySQL doesn't have RLS which means they **have** to have their security layer tied to the API, so I doubt even if they wanted to, no security person there would ever give raw SQL access **especially** because they have a multi-tenant database architecture, which means they store multiple tenants (orgs) on teh same database.

Overall we have a massive moat still with SQLite. I think it will be actually impossible for them to give raw SQL access, especially with the "conservative" decision making they keep bringing up in every article I've read from their engineering field.

FOr example I asked what were people talking aboput yesterday and it generated this:

```sql
SELECT message.message, message.createdAt, user.fullName, channel.slug AS channelName 
FROM message 
JOIN user ON message.userId = user.userId 
JOIN channel ON message.channelId = channel.id 
WHERE message.createdAt >= (strftime('%s', 'now', '-2 days') + 0) * 1000
AND message.createdAt < (strftime('%s', 'now', '-1 day') + 0) * 1000
LIMIT 100
```
